  "text": "A recent follow-up study reported that patients with the CHEK2 1100delC variant had a high risk of contralateral breast cancer (relative risk, 5.7; 95% CI, 1.7-19.7; ref. 15) . This finding is supported by other studies that reported a six times higher prevalence of CHEK2 1100delC carriers among patients with bilateral breast cancer, as compared with patients with unilateral breast cancer [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Surprisingly, we saw a similar prevalence of bilateral cases among Polish women with a CHEK2 mutation (2.3%), compared with those without a CHEK2 mutation (3.3%), but the numbers were small and we restricted our analysis to early-onset cases.",
